I. INTRODUCTION
What is an economist’s job like? A good metaphor helps economists reflect the nature
of economics as a discipline and their role in society. It has been described as dentists (e.g.
Keynes 1930), engineers (e.g. Mankiw 2006; Colander 2013a; Roth 2002), and surgeons (Romer
2016). One of the most recent and intriguing analogies was given by Esther Duflo at her
American Economic Association Richard Ely Lecture in 2017 (Duflo 2017). She compares part
of economists’ job with that of a plumber, and urges economists to adopt a mindset of the
plumber for their work.
For most economists, who consider economics the queen of social sciences, Duflo’s
metaphor is no doubt radical, and probably a bit insulting and humiliating. Dentists, surgeons
and engineers are at least professionals, and closer to the scientists which most economists think
of themselves as. But plumber? That may be pushing the boundary for economists’ humility
quotient. Nevertheless, Duflo’s plumber metaphor is more than a call for humility; it involves
examining how economics should be done. Hence, whether her metaphor makes sense or not
does not depend on how the economics profession feels about it, but whether economists can do
a better job if they adopt the mindset of plumber. The same logic applies to other metaphors.
In this paper we argue that economists should be playing all these jobs and more,
because economics is not a single entity, and each entity is better done with different
methodologies and mindsets. This view is directly related to the question of what the boundaries
of economics should be. We suggest that an additional new set of boundaries is needed besides
the conventional disciplinary boundaries. Traditionally, the boundaries of economics are drawn
to define the disciplinary domain. In many economist’s mind, the boundaries of economics as a
2
discipline are implicitly specified in reference to science (whatever science means to them). If
one takes this view, one sees doing economics as doing science, an economist as a scientist.
The standard way of thinking of boundaries is, in our view, insufficient in that it
subjects all aspects of economics to the same boundaries when it makes much more sense for
different aspects of economics, especially economic science and applied economics, to have
different boundaries.1
A key reason to differentiate the boundaries is that applied work is likely to face
different problems than scientific work. Policy, for example, falls within the boundary of applied
economics, but to the degree it requires integrating normative judgements, it needs to go outside
the boundary of scientific economics for aspects of its work. Differentiating the boundaries
between applied work and scientific work helps us make sense of Duflo’s metaphor and adds
insight into the role of economists. We believe that Duflo, and modern economists generally, do
not adequately recognize the usefulness of separating science from applied work; they have a
strong tendency to think of applied economics and economic science as having overlapping and
congruent boundaries. This causes economists to fall short in various roles which they should
fulfil. We argue that “scientist” should not be the overall category within which all economists fit.
Economics includes science, but it is not just science. The boundaries of scientific economics
should not be confused with the boundaries of economics.
Like skin, while being a constraint, allows the body to form a shape, boundaries of
economics legitimize economists’ focusing on one dimension of multi-facetted social
phenomena and adopting the appropriate methods for their study. The boundaries also signify the
1 In this paper, we use the terms “scientific economics” and “economic science” interchangeably.
3
jobs most economists do and the roles they play. Boundaries of economics matter. Hence, before
examining what roles economists should play in the final section, we first argue in Section II that
a new way of thinking about the boundaries is needed as it is essential for the economics
profession to improve its ability to provide relevant and quality policy analysis. We outline our
suggested approach with a focus on what we mean by “applied economics” in Section III. We
then in Section IV bring the argument back to Duflo’s plumbing metaphor, and argue that a
better metaphor for the point she is making would be a “general contractor” analogy. The general
applied policy economist is best seen as the person who brings economic specialists together--the
scientist, the craftsman, the plumber and the engineer to achieve some goal; the general
economist needs to be an all-rounder, knowing to whom to go for specialized knowledge. The
boundaries of the general contractor’s focus are indeterminate and dependent on the problem
being considered.
II. BOUNDARIES MATTER
The conventional way of drawing boundaries: its function and insufficiency
From the late eighteenth century to the early twentieth century, the boundaries of
economics were drawn by subject matter, namely, wealth and material welfare. Changes in
boundaries occurred over time, away from material wealth boundaries. By the end of 1960s, the
scope of economics was no longer defined as the study of wealth, but instead by the theoretical
model used to study choice—constrained optimization, and the empirical implementation of that
model with econometrics.
Even though the boundaries of economics presented in the textbooks may appear to be
similar for more than fifty years since 1960s, the actual boundaries have never stopped evolving
4
as what economists do continues changing, some of which is on the edge of economics or even
outside the boundaries. The lively development of economics in the past few decades has
significantly changed the face of economics as well as its boundaries.
For instance, with the development of behavioral economics, and with game theory
replacing calculus as the theoretical engine of analysis, modern economics widened its
boundaries to include a wider range of empirical methods. Econometrics was supplemented by
various types of experiments. Economists adopted carefully specified experimental methods and
randomized controlled trials became the gold standard for applied micro economists. Boundaries
have shifted: they are no longer defined by constrained optimization. Instead, what used to be
seen at the margin or outside economics has been recognized as the mainstream. The fact that
Daniel Kahneman and Richard Thaler, pioneer behavioral economists, won the Nobel prizes in
2002 and 2018, and that Abhijit Banerjee, Esther Duflo and Michael Kremer were the winners in
2019 for transforming development economics with experimental research methods is a good
demonstration for this. Boundaries have shifted: even though it is not clear where exactly the
new boundaries of economics are and what holds them together.
Either defined by wealth or methods, the above-mentioned boundaries in the different
phases of the history of economics have all served a similar function, that is, to delineate the
scope of economics as a discipline in order to differentiate its subject-matter and methods from
other disciplines. Conceptualizing boundaries in this way per se is not a problem. However,
problems arise when such disciplinary boundaries are assumed to be the boundaries of a science.
Our argument is that boundaries of economics as a whole are not the same as
boundaries of economic science. Thinking about boundaries of economics in terms of boundaries
5
of economic science, in our view, misses an important element of the boundary dispute. It forces
one to see the challenge faced by economics profession through a narrow perspective and as a
result, issues beyond the boundaries of economic science tend to be neglected, in particular,
issues in the policy domain. Therefore, we argue that a new way of thinking boundaries is
needed. Specifically, the overarching boundary between science and applied policy needs to be
recognized, with each activity being seen as having its own scope and method.
Introducing an extra set of boundaries: a revival of the classical tradition
Our proposal to draw boundaries between economic science and applied economics is
by no means novel. It is actually a call for returning to the classical tradition that treats
conducting scientific economic enquires and providing economic policy advice as separate
activities with different natures. Hence, it is important to articulate what this tradition is.
Nassau Senior (1790-1864) is one of the key figures attempting to establish economics
as a science in early nineteenth century England. In his book An Outline of The Science of
Political Economy ([1836] 1951), he clearly announces a breakup with economists before him
and confines political economy to be a scientific study of the nature, the production and the
distribution of wealth.⁠ As the first Drummond Professor of Political Economy at Oxford, the first
chair of political economy in England, Senior’s approach to economics was well received at the
time.
In a similar vein, John Stuart Mill (1806-1873) made a more thorough and complete
discussion on treating political economy as science. In Mill’s hand, political economy became a
separate discipline in two senses. First, it was a discipline separate from other social sciences;
second, it was a scientific discipline separate from ethics.
6
Because of the separation in the first sense, it was possible for classical political
economists to examine economic phenomena without constantly blending political and
sociological elements into their formal study. Economics becoming a separate discipline was
accompanied by the division of labor, allowing different disciplines to study specific dimensions
of social phenomena with the methods appropriate for the investigation. However, this advantage
came with a cost. The conclusions reached by individual disciplines were partial. It follows that
the conclusions reached by economics alone cannot provide policy prescription. Once the
disciplines had separated, to reach a policy recommendation, a collaboration among disciplines
became required.
With the limitation of economics as a separate discipline in mind, those economists we
classified in the classical tradition2 all share a similar view on constraining themselves from
making policy advice by grounding based on economic theorems alone. For instance, at the
beginning of his book, Senior issued a warning that it is not the job of an economist to
recommend or dissuade using the conclusion of economic science as the sole or principal guides
in actual conduct of affairs. One of the key reasons for Senior to justify this warning is that
policy making requires considering all the causes which may promote or impede the general
human welfare whilst economists as scientific theorist have considered only one of them, namely,
wealth. (Senior [1836] 1951, pp. 2-3)
Similarly, Mill is fully aware of the limitation caused by the artificially drawn
boundaries. He gave a clear warning about it. In this context, Mill stresses that “the mere
political economist, he who has studied no science but Political Economy, if he attempt to apply
2 Note that this does not include Adam Smith.
7
his science to practice, will fail” (Mill [1844] 1967, p. 331) and “the didactic writer on the
subject will naturally combine in his exposition, with the truths of the pure science, as many of
the practical modifications as will, in his estimation, be most conducive to the usefulness of his
work” (Mill [1844] 1967, p. 323). These statements are made to appeal for attention to the
problem caused by the isolation of political economy from other social sciences, rather than
ethics.
Our call here is to revive this Classical recognition of the difference between economic
science and applied economics. Using Colander’s (2013b) words, it is necessary to keep a
firewall between theorems of economic science and policy advice.
This Classical tradition was further elaborated and summarized by John Neville Keynes
in his Scope and Method of Political Economy (1890) in which he distinguished three branches
of economics—normative, positive, and art. Normative economics was a philosophical
consideration of the goals. Positive economics was a scientific consideration of the workings of
the economy. The art of economics was a blend of the two, with vaguely defined boundaries and
in large part non-economic. Boundaries depended on which branch one is working in. Applied
economics belonged in the art of economics, which meant that it had different boundaries than
did the science of economics. Within this tradition, whatever the scope and method of positive
economics was, the methodology of applied policy economics was not dependent on it, and
should be considered separately.
Rethinking the boundaries
This Classical tradition was lost in first half of the twentieth century, and was gradually
replaced with the new approach that did not differentiate the boundaries of economic science and
8
applied policy. In the new approach one moves directly from the theoretical conclusions to
policy prescription (Colander 2009, 2011, 2018).
Here we do not intend to give a thorough review of how the classical tradition got lost
as it is beyond the scope of the paper. Rather, we use Robbins, who is usually seen as the turning
point of the changing boundaries in the early twentieth century, as an example to demonstrate the
difference between the conventional understanding of boundaries and the boundaries we are
advocating in this paper.
In principle, the additional set of boundaries proposed in this paper is to delineate
different entities within the discipline of economics as a whole. It is different from the traditional
concept of boundaries that drawing the outer boundaries of economics as a discipline. Failing to
recognize the difference of the two is one of the main causes leading to misinterpret Robbins’s
position, a misinterpretation that had significantly influenced the development of economics in
the twentieth century.
The misinterpretation is understandable given that boundaries were still understood in
the conventional sense while Robbins was in effect drawing the boundaries of economics in a
new sense without being aware of the difference. In his well-known book Essay on the Nature
and Significance of Economic Science, Robbins argued that the science of economics had no
place for value judgements, and that the theoretical branch of economics could be defined as “the
science which studies human behavior as a relationship between ends and scarce means which
have alternative uses” (Robbins [1932] 1935, p. 16). He also argued that there was no scientific
basis for interpersonal utility comparisons and hence they could not be part of scientific
economics. Robbins’s position has been understood as one arguing that if interpersonal
9
comparisons couldn’t be made in science, they couldn’t be made in economics. Indeed,
according to the conventional account of history of economics (e.g. Blaug 1997), Robbins’s
argument undermined the utilitarian foundations of Pigovian applied policy welfare economics
and led to the rise of the new welfare economics based on social welfare functions. But it only
holds if applied policy economics is interpreted as having to fall within the boundaries of science.
That was not what Robbins intended.
As Robbins argued in his Ely Lecture, what he intended to suggest is that economists
deal with normative judgements in a different branch of economics separate from the scientific
branch of economics. He calls this branch Political Economy. According to Robbins, Political
Economy applies the technical apparatus of analytical economics to realize aims whose
formulation lies outside economics in the stricter sense of the word, namely, scientific economics.
Political Economy involves not only all the models of analysis, but also “explicit or implicit
judgements of value that are usually involved when economists discuss assessments of benefits
and the reverse or recommendations for policy” (Robbins 1981, p. 8).
Thus, in Robbins’s vision of economics, there would be both a scientific branch and an
active applied policy branch that dealt with integrating scientific and ethical elements.
Economics after him did not follow this path. Because it wasn’t appreciated by later economists
that applied economics had different boundaries and nature other than scientific economics,
Robbins’s attempt to define the boundaries of scientific economics to not include moral
considerations had the unintended and undesirable side effect of excluding serious consideration
of moral analysis from applied policy economics, precisely the opposite of his intention.
Why the new concept of boundaries is important
10
With the new concept of boundaries, we believe, economists could better understand the
nature of different entities of economics and better communicate with each other. It is fair to say
that failing to draw boundaries between different entities of economics has prevented economists
from communicating effectively and caused obstacles to reforming economics. A noticeable
example is the apparent conflict between those who argue for developing more complex models
and those who intend to bring ethics back to economics in reaction to the 2008 financial crisis.
The former considers the problem of economics to be that its models are too simple to capture
the complexity of economic systems. In contrast, the latter blames the mainstream economics for
neglecting ethical considerations and argues that this problem cannot be addressed by adopting
different models however complex they are.
At first glance, these two views seem to be irreconcilable. But the disagreement is only
apparent because the problems these two camps try to solve actually fall into two different
branches of economics. For those who attempt to adopt more complex models, the concept of
economics in their mind is mainly the scientific branch of economics. In contrast, in the mind of
those who intend to bring ethics back to economics, the concept of economics mainly falls in the
applied policy branch of economics. In our view, both changes are needed, but they involve quite
different methodologies. To argue that ethics has to be integrated into economic analysis based
on scientific methodology makes it much more difficult to integrate them in. Accepting that
science and applied policy have different boundaries allows a richer discussion of applied policy
issues.
It is important to note that not all studies related to ethics will necessarily fall into the
realm of applied economics. What separates the scientific branch of economics from the applied
one is not the exclusion of issues concerning moral norms or moral preferences, but the absence
11
of normative judgements. In the past two decades, with abundant empirical evidences, a growing
literature attempts to disprove narrow interpretations of Homo economicus, a classic assumption
of human nature in mainstream economics. Samuel Bowles for one demonstrates in his book The
Moral Economy (2016) with evidences from laboratory and field experiments that moral and
other noneconomic motives and preferences such as altruism, reciprocity, trust and so on often
play crucial roles in influencing our economic behavior, including in the market and non-market
setting. Despite being used for recommendations for policy design, the analysis of how human
behavior is influenced by moral norms as well as moral preferences is a study of “what is”, not
“what ought to be”. Such an study should follow scientific methods, and this type of study
should not be conflated with the study of ethics as it often happens today. This likely confusion
was anticipated by J. N. Keynes who argued that ‘political economy may recognize the operation
of moral motives in the economic world, and yet not become an ethical science’ (Keynes [1890]
1917, p. 46). Studying moral dispositions or moral behavior as a fact is a business quite different
from studying how these facts can and should help inform the formulation of policy.
We do not pretend that reintroducing the boundaries between the scientific branch of
economics and the applied branch of economics will resolve all the problems faced by
economics. It is true that this old classification is not perfect and has some challenges awaiting
answers. Yet, discarding this tradition because of its imperfection is like throwing the baby out
with the bathwater.
As the allocation of scarce resource definition of all economics lost its significance and
the corresponding boundaries of economics crumbled, it is now time for economists to
reconsider the path that was not taken in the early twentieth century and returning to the
12
boundaries of economics that Robbins intended to draw, which require a separation of applied
economics from scientific economics.
IV. APPLIED ECONOMICS
It is not an easy task to draw boundaries between scientific economics and applied
policy economics even if one accepts the necessity of drawing such boundaries. One of the
difficulties results from the fact that the meaning of “applied” is vague and the concept of
“application” in economics is a loose one. Since the term “applied economics” has been used by
economists to refer to several different things, let us first make it clear what we mean by applied
economics or the applied branch of economics.
Nature, scope and methodology
We can easily identify at least three meanings commonly used among economists. First,
it means empirical work used to test the validity of theory. Second, it means the application of
theoretical conclusions to policy advice. Third, it means the application of theoretical cores to
various fields (see Backhouse and Biddle 2000; Backhouse and Cherrier 2017; Cherrier 2017).
Our focus is on the second of these—applied policy economics. Accordingly, we are quite
comfortable with the above first and third types of work belonging to a category called science as
long as their aim is to find facts, rather than to guide policy or action. But the second category is
best separated out as having different boundaries.
If we map our distinction between economic science and applied policy economics to J.
N. Keynes’s tripartite division of economics, applied policy economics roughly corresponds to
an art of political economy.
13
Despite coining the term ‘art of political economy’, Keynes is actually cautious with
using it as he worried that it may cause misunderstanding as if it is a body of precepts which can
be completed exclusively based on the science of economics. Keynes’s concern reflects the
difficulty of drawing clear-cut boundaries of applied economics due to its multidisciplinary
character.
Even though the boundaries of applied economics are fuzzy, we can still roughly
categorize the knowledge belonging to applied economics into three types.
 First, knowledge from other scientific disciplines (not only mathematics, physics
from which economics used to borrow the tools or concepts, but more importantly,
the neighboring disciplines in social sciences and humanities, such as psychology,
political science, sociology, social and cultural anthropology, human geography,
history, etc.)
 Second, non-scientific knowledge that does not involve moral values. This
includes knowledge which is not systematically derived from scientific and
organized disciplines but obtained from individual experience and observation.
This type of knowledge is often dispersed among individuals, causing difficulty
for policy making (Hayek 1945).
 Third, knowledge regarding morals.
Because applied policy has to incorporate these different types of knowledge in order to
reach objective conclusions, the methods appropriate for applied economics are different from
those appropriate for economic science. Unlike economic science which has to strictly follow
14
scientific methods, applied policy economics adopts much wider ranges of methods—using
philosophical methods to deal with moral issues, and engineering methods to deal with non-
economic issues that are important but have not yet been answered by science. This does not
mean anything goes; it simply means that applied policy is a craft that practitioners develop.
Each specialty has what engineering methodologist Billy Vaughn Koen (2003) calls the “state of
the art”. We call this applied policy method of doing applied economics the engineering
approach subject to the engineering methodology spelled out by Koen.
An economist dealing with policy would use a methodology different from scientific
methodology. On the one hand it is less restrictive; it allows back-of-the-envelope calculations
and rough estimation of needed parameters. On the other hand, it demands knowledge and
judgements far beyond scientific knowledge. Engineering is not science precisely because it is
concerned with solutions to problems, not purely understanding. If a policy seems to work, even
if inconsistent with current scientific theory, the economic engineer will use it, adding a “fudge
factor” to account for the lack of firm scientific basis. The reason is that economists as engineers
are required to do much more than applying scientific theories, and will be limited in their role if
they are required to always follow scientific methodology.
Engineering methodology includes scientific methodology, but is more expansive, and
far less restrictive. Engineers determine the controlling methodology for how much science,
other knowledge, and moral reasoning are used, following current best practices.3
Where to draw the line: an illustration
