2018, Chapter 8.
15
Admittedly, it is not easy to draw clear boundaries between scientific and applied
economics. At the conceptual level, these two branches are clear. The difficulty of drawing the
lines resides mainly in the fact that in practice these two branches often exist together.
Economists can easily move from one realm to the other in the same piece of work without being
aware that they have crossed the boundaries. Even the first-class economists could fail to
appreciate adequately the difference in the nature of science and policy and consequently impair
the quality of their policy analysis with restrictive methods unsuitable for policy.
Take Raj Chetty as an example. “Yes, economics is a science”, he announces, in his
defense of economics against skeptics who charge it to be a fake science after the Nobel Prize in
Economic Sciences were awarded to economists of opposing views on the same issue in the
same year (Chetty 2013). Chetty’s own work largely aims at making economics an empirical
science, a science like medicine. Most of his economic research indeed deserves the name of
science and “has the ability to inform policy decisions on the basis of evidence instead of
ideology” as he wishes. However, applying empirical findings directly for policy guidance
without drawing a line between policy and science could lead to misleading conclusions as if
policy ought to be studied with scientific methods and nothing else. This can be shown in one of
Chetty’s works on taxation.
In his paper “Salience and Taxation”, Chetty and his co-authors use a field and quasi-
experiments to show that the visibility of the tax-inclusive price matters to the consumption
behaviour (Chetty et al. 2009). Their experiments demonstrate that how consumers react to taxes
can be studied empirically, and how the empirical results from experiments can be used to inform
policy design. Yet, as soon as they move to the discussion of the implications of their empirical
results for tax policy, they lose their grounding. In discussing how their results affect policy, they
16
integrate those results into a standard formal welfare policy analysis. In so doing, they develop a
formal theoretical framework for applied welfare analysis that they argue can accommodate
salience effects, which they characterize as an optimization error made by consumers.
The welfare analysis done in the paper is full of scientific aura, but it focuses solely on
“efficiency costs” and completely neglects any discussion of fundamental issues that from an
engineering perspective, will likely be highly important, such as fairness and transparency. The
experiments show that posting tax-inclusive price tags reduces demand, which suggests that tax-
exclusive prices might fool buyers into spending more than they intended. “All-inclusive
pricing”, as Werner Antweiler (2016) points out, “is thus a matter of fairness and transparency”.
An apparent scientific policy analysis can produce conclusions more biased than an engineering
analysis that explicitly includes considerations that cannot be studied scientifically. In the case of
policy analysis, the attempt of being scientific doesn't guarantee objectivity.
Chetty’s case is not unique. In fact, Chetty’s faith in scientific economics informing
policy decision is commonly shared by the champions of evidence-based policy, an approach
which has become the vogue for policymaking in many different areas across several countries,
among international organizations and NGOs over the past two decades. In the field of
development economics, evidence-based policymaking has been extensively applied to issues
such as poverty, schooling, healthcare, etc. The urge for evidence-based policymaking in
accounting and financial markets regulation is also on the rise in recent years.4 The evidence-
4 For the opportunities and challenges of adopting evidence-based approach for accounting and
financial policies and regulations, see Leuz (2018).
17
based policy movement aims to improve the quality of decision-making by replacing policy-
making based on ideologies or faiths with those based on scientific evidence.
We appreciate the intention of improving the quality of policymaking by grounding it
on robust empirical evidences, but the standard randomized controlled trials (RCTs), which play
a major role in the evidence-based policy approach, are inadequate in answering at least two key
issues of policy analysis. First, on the analytical and explanatory side, conceptual frameworks
and judgments are required to make sense of data and evidence and to identify the causal
mechanism; what is considered evidence depends on one’s framework. As is the case with the
traditional deductive methods in scientific economics, the conclusions derived from the
experimental inductive methods are incomplete and far from definitive: their validity is subject
to the external context. Using the phrases of Cartwright and Hardie (2012), “it worked there”
does not guarantee “it will work here”.5 Second, on the prescriptive side, evidence and data alone
tell us nothing about how the desirability and priorities of policy goals ought to be determined.
5 This limitation of randomized field experiments is recognized by Banerjee and Duflo in a paper
where they responded to the criticisms concerning the environmental dependence of
