(Banerjee and Duflo 2009, 2017).
18
In summary, scientific evidence can inform policy, but cannot be directly translated into
policy recommendations.6 Ultimately, the practice of basing policy on rigorous scientific
evidence does not make policy analysis and policymaking the sole business of science. Drawing
boundaries between scientific economics and applied economics is crucial for economists to
better grasp the strengths and limitations of the empirical approaches in economic science as well
as their implications to applied economic policy analysis and policymaking.
V. SHOULD ECONOMISTS THINK OF THEMSELVES AS PLUMBERS?
Now that we have developed our arguments, let us return to the metaphor with which
we began the paper—Duflo’s metaphor of economists as plumbers. While we are largely in
agreement with the fundamental point of Duflo’s argument—that applied policy economists need
to take practical implementation problems seriously, we find her metaphor of economist-as-
plumber problematic, and symptomatic of the type problems that arise when scientific economics
and applied policy economics are not differentiated. Put simply, plumbers aren’t scientists, and
for her argument to make sense, economists must accept that it isn’t realistic that an economist
fills both roles. There are at least three issues to be considered with Duflo’s metaphor.
Division of labor and specialization
6 Partly because of this reason, Christian Leuz considers the more modest term “evidence-
informed policymaking” is preferred to “evidence-based policymaking” (Leuz, 2018, p. 600,
emphasis original).
19
The first is the division of labor among economists. This can be considered in two
aspects: first, who should do what in view of the expected roles; second, who is capable of doing
what in view of their training and skills.
Duflo argues that economists should act like plumbers in addition to scientists and
engineers. In her view, each of these mindsets has an important role in policy design: “Scientists
design general frames, engineers turn them into relevant machinery, and plumbers finally make
them work in a complicated, messy policy environment” (Duflo 2017, p. 23). This statement
suggests that for Duflo there are no clear boundaries between science and policy. One of the
potential consequences of mixing the two domains is that scientists are doing something they
cannot do properly if they strictly follow the methodological rules of science.
In contrast to Duflo, we believe that it is economic engineers, not economic scientists,
who should design policy just like it is engineers, not scientists, who are responsible for
designing machines. Designing a reliable machine requires solid scientific knowledge, but
designing a machine per se is not the same as doing science. Similarly, designing a policy is not
the same as doing science, even though the chance for a policy to function properly would
generally be higher if the design of policy is informed by solid scientific evidence.
Another consequence of not adequately differentiating applied policy from economic
science is that the division of labor would likely work less effectively due to the training based
on specialization. According to Duflo, one of the key reasons why economists need the mindset
of a plumber is due to economists’ limited knowledge of the issues at hand. In her words, there
are the “unknown unknowns” that we cannot predict but that will arise anyway. Unlike
economist-as-scientist and economist-as-engineer, the economist-as-plumber “does not have the
20
safety net of a bounded set of assumptions” (2017, p. 3). She has to face and resolve the
problems which do not appear in the models, but do arise in the real world. “If the specific real-
world problem at hand cannot be solved analytically”, Duflo suggests, the economist-as-plumber
“will reach for other tools” (2017, p. 3). She sees field experimentation as an important tool in
the economist-as-plumber’s toolkit.
We agree that the plumber, when laying down the pipe, needs to use all sorts of
knowledge and tools available to her in order to make the plumbing work. However, Duflo’s
plumber metaphor is not suitable for her own purpose, because some jobs delegated by Duflo to
the economist-as-plumber would easily go beyond a plumber’s training and skills. Field
experiments are done by scientists and they follow a well-specified scientific methodology. To
appropriately conduct a randomized field experiment requires a high level of scientific
knowledge and good working knowledge of these methods. Arguably, it is the innovation in
scientific method, rather than the plumbing, entailed in Duflo’s experimental approach to
development economics that won her the title of Nobel Laurate in economic sciences. To do
these experiments right one needs training in scientific methodology; it is unlikely to be done
properly by a plumber who does not have significant training in science or even in engineering.
The difference between a real plumber and an economic scientist imagining herself to
be a plumber can be seen by comparing her approach to that of a self-declared non scientist, Paul
Polak (1931-2019). Polak was a psychiatrist and real estate developer who decided he had plenty
of money and he wanted to spend the rest of his life helping the poor, which he defined as those
with income under $1 a day. He developed a twelve-step guide to practical problem solving that
did not involve randomized control experiments, and he would consider such formal methods as
part and parcel of the failed development efforts that characterize academic approaches to
21
helping the poor. His methodological guides include: Go where the action is. Listen to those who
have the problem. Learn everything you can about the problem’s specific context. Think like a
child. Design to specific cost and price targets. (Polak, 2008, p. 14) None of his directives
involved any economic theory, other than the obvious. None involved formal testing; it was too
expensive. It involved informal testing, trial and error, and correction on the fly. It involved all
types of practical knowledge, but no economic theory. One of his solutions to poverty—low cost
treadle pumps and drip irrigation systems made with inexpensive piping where drip hoses were
created by punching nails in pipe—totally involved plumbing. But it did not involve applied
economists, other than for the economist to recognize that such bottom-up development offers
enormous possibilities that will not be recognized by economists who are not laser focused on an
objective of helping the poor. Polak’s guides are plumbing heuristics, which are grounded on
crystalized plumbing knowledge obtained and accumulated through learning by doing in the field.
We argue that such plumbing heuristics, knowledge, and approaches, even though not scientific,
have great value for practical problem solving, and deserve the attention of economist-as-
engineer when designing economic policies, particularly when scientific knowledge is not
available.7
Economists as general contractors
7 What is called “plumbing knowledge” here corresponds to the second type of knowledge
classified in Section IV. Plumbing heuristics are normative, but their establishment are not
entirely independent from plumbing knowledge, which are positive. Linking the two requires
sensibilities and judgments that go beyond science.
22
The economist as plumber could be a useful metaphor in the right context, but it does
not work well for the type of job to which Duflo refers. Instead of picturing hands-on applied
policy economists as plumbers, we suggest that it would be best to picture them as general
contractors. “General contractor economists” are the economists who actually carry out the
translation of policy design into real world policy.
A general contractor has an overview of the entire project—she is in constant contact
with engineers, plumbers, carpenters, architects, mechanical technicians, and she also knows,
and works with, the customer of the policy integrating his values into the design of the policy.
She doesn’t get an abstract social welfare function given to her. She works with the customer to
determine the content of it, often guiding the customer as to what is feasible and desirable, and
how best to achieve the desired policy goals. Sometimes she plays a relatively value neutral
advisory scientific-like engineering role—given the state-of-the-art knowledge, here is what is
achievable. Other times she plays a psychological advisor role in which she blends normative
and positive aspects of analysis together as an artist would. She translates the customer’s
generally vaguely understood vision into a practical buildable vision. Doing this job well
requires going far beyond what can be determined by science.
Obviously, in real life economists fulfill many different roles. They are scientists,
engineers, and general contractors. That’s what makes economics so difficult. Our point is not
that they should not play multiple roles—it is that they should match their methodology to fit the
role that they are playing.
Taking morals and value judgement seriously
23
In Duflo’s discussion, the major task for the economist-as-plumber is to make sure the
policy, once implemented, will function effectively to achieve the assigned goals. In other words,
what is deemed as desirable goals that a policy aims to achieve has already been determined in
some way and is not under question or dispute. Duflo’s discussion does not explore how the
goals are determined. Presumably, it is not a job of the economist-as-plumber. Instead it is the
job for the economists as design engineer and the economist as general contractor. This indicates
the incompleteness of the plumber metaphor for applied economics.
Moreover, even if there is no disagreement concerning the goals of a policy, when there
is no consensus in scientific findings, what should economists do in order to provide policy
guidelines? The disagreement over the conclusions derived from economic science can result
from many different reasons, but often they do not result from the different views in goals or
from fundamentally different views of science. Disagreements often result from differences in
sensibilities, which scientific methodology cannot resolve. To resolve these disagreements, the
research institutions and the methodology must be designed to arrive at conclusions about these
heuristic judgements. There is no absolute.
In Duflo’s examples, those details missing in scientific models, yet essential for policy
design, are mostly related to the complexity of human behavior and preference. When they do
not match the assumptions of models, on which policy design is based, then policy will not work.
Hence, Duflo emphasizes the importance of behavioral economics, network economics, and
informational economics. In one sense, behavioral economics and informational economics
adjust the policy design by correcting the assumptions of the scientific models, on which the
policy design is originally grounded. But the deviation of what happens in reality from what
models predicts can be caused by reasons other than unrealistic assumptions.
24
These other aspects of applied economics that have been lost are not something that
plumbers could resolve. Science has no problem with adding issues of plumbing in Duflo’s sense.
It does have a problem with adding those aspects of policy that relate to values and sensibilities.
Thinking of economists as plumbers will not integrate moral values back into applied analysis,
marking the second major weakness of Duflo’s metaphor. The more important change will only
occur when the profession develops a methodology that recognizes that policy follows from
various types of judgement (moral or amoral, factual or normative).
Training
We have been noting the shortcomings of the plumber metaphor, but we are not
quibbling over words but rather with the sensibility associated with the words. Our interest is in
how the metaphors affect economist’s training. We see a much larger need for change than does
Duflo. This is the third reason why we consider Duflo’s plumber metaphor unfit. She seems to
believe that economists, with the current training, are well prepared for taking up the plumber’s
role and that this requires only a change in mindsets, not a major change in training.8 We don’t
see this as an accurate description of the current training of economists or as a right prescription
8 It is Duflo’s view that “economists have the disciplinary training to make good plumbers”
(2017, p. 15) and that “plumbing should be an inherent part of our profession: we are well
prepared for it, reasonably good at it” (2017, p. 23). By “training” here, she mainly refers to the
training in behavioral science, incentive issues and firm behavior.
25
to move forward; we see economists needing not only changes in mindset, but also in how they
are educated. That training would be more differentiated than it currently is.9
There would be differentiated scientific and engineering training, just as there is in most
fields. Graduate programs would not be ranked on a unidimensional scale. Some top programs
would specialize in science and some in engineering and general contracting. Most economists
going on into undergraduate teaching would benefit most from general contracting training—
seeing how good applied policy requires approaching a policy problem from multiple directions
and the need to bring various skills to the table.
Those focusing on engineering and general contracting roles of economists would
provide more training in engineering heuristics and general contracting and less in abstract
theory. While the actual craft of plumbing might not be taught, the applied economist would be
introduced to it and taught its importance, just as they would be introduced to ethics, aesthetics,
politics, psychology, etc., and taught their importance. That training would be significantly
different than economist’s current training, and it goes far beyond teaching that plumbing is
9 There have been many calls for change in the curriculum but ours is somewhat different from
many of them such as the recent INET Core initiative. (https://www.core-econ.org/ See also
Bowles and Carlin, forthcoming). Their call for change concerns the coverage and presentation.
Ours focuses more on methodology, arguing that methods appropriate for science and methods
appropriate for policy are fundamentally different. In our view, identifying and highlighting this
difference in Econ 101 is of much more significance for economics education reform than
broadening the coverage of topics and schools of thought.
26
important. Such a change in training can only occur if economics distinguishes separate
boundaries for science and applied policy.
J. M. Keynes’s description of a master economists captures what we believe the training
should be designed to achieve:10
[T]he master-economist must possess a rare combination of gifts. [...] He must be
mathematician, historian, statesman, philosopher—in some degree. He must understand
symbols and speak in words. He must contemplate the particular in terms of the general,
and touch abstract and concrete in the same flight of thought. He must study the present
in the light of the past for the purposes of the future. No part of man's nature or his
institutions must lie entirely outside his regard. He must be purposeful and disinterested
in a simultaneous mood; as aloof and incorruptible as an artist, yet sometimes as near
the earth as a politician. (Keynes 1924, p. 322, emphasis original)
If economist’s training could be structured to let students know that a master economist is an all-
rounder, needing many different skills, that would be wonderful.
